works

Comparison of Photorealism in Game Engines for Synthetic Maritime Computer Vision Datasets - Master's Thesis

To advance ship recognition and maritime awareness, this project explores the use of game engines to generate photorealistic synthetic datasets. By comparing Unity and Unreal Engine, we analyse their effectiveness in creating high-quality synthetic maritime images, ultimately improving computer vision models for ship segmentation.

The thesis was made possible in coordination with the DLR (German Aerospace Center), Bremerhaven.

Smart Helmet

As per the engineering curriculum, we are accustomed to build a project based on the subjects from our curriculum. The project that has been accepted by IEEE Technically Co-Sponsored ‘3rd Biennial International Conference on Nascent Technologies in Engineering’ for a technical paper presentation held on 4th & 5th January 2019.

Learn more

Tiltification

Tiltification is a multi-modal spirit level app designed to make sonification—a method of conveying information through sound—more accessible and widely recognised. Developed as part of the "Sonification Apps" project at the University of Bremen, the app utilises psychoacoustic sonification to provide real-time auditory feedback on a device’s tilt angles, enabling users to level surfaces or capture perfectly horizontal photos.

Learn more

]]> 284 0 0 0 ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> <![CDATA[Design Proposal for a Simple Calculator]]> https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/design-proposal-for-a-simple-calculator/ Wed, 09 Jun 2021 13:16:22 +0000 https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/?page_id=315

As part of the Interface Design course in Winter Semester 2020, a design proposal for Calculator was put forth. The goal was to design a calculator that enhances the user's proficiency in arithmetic calculations.

The calculator visually demonstrates the calculation process following the BODMAS rule, highlighting each operation step by step.

The course was conducted under the guidance of Prof. Peter von Maydell.

References

"A New Calculator and Why it is Necessary" by Harold Thimbleby

"Evaluating a Novel Calculator Interface" by Paul Cairns, Sameera Wali, and Harold Thimbleby

"Task-Specific Performance Effects with Different Numeric Keypads Layout" by Jenny T. Armand, Thomas S. Redick, and Joan R. Poulsen

]]> 315 0 0 0 ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> <![CDATA[Custom Styles]]> https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/2022/03/29/wp-global-styles-pub%2fspearhead/ Tue, 29 Mar 2022 16:13:52 +0000 https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/2022/03/29/wp-global-styles-pub%2fspearhead/ 344 0 0 0 <![CDATA[Hurricane]]> https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/hurricane/ Tue, 29 Mar 2022 16:41:55 +0000 https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/?page_id=348

Idea

The idea about the design comes from the fact that a landmark is redeveloping into a new space. The newly redeveloped space should behold the landmark status plus resonate with the architectural style of the locality. The proposed structure is a mix of a transition from the Historic to Modern along with sections that appear to float. Both of these approaches have been blended with the weather that the city experiences. Thus, “Hurricane”.

Design & Technique

We incorporated our ideas while sketching them out. Two dominant parameters of Floating and Historic to Modern were selected. The total area that is to be redeveloped was measured with Google Earth. Following this, a scale of 1:250 was calculated.

Models were created with Rhino and Blender. Rhino gave flexibility with the models as their size can now be changed easily. With Blender, we could match our design into the existing space. The models were then converted into 2-dimensional and then cut out with the laser cutter. This approach made the realisation of the models easy. The material used is a mix of paper, glass acrylic and wood. For the garden and trees models, moss and twigs were collected. The collected moss was cultivated indoors and the twigs were modelled to look like trees.

Function

The floating bridge serves as MENSA and a Café. It’s position faces one of the main streets. This adds to the fascination and highlights the entire structure to the public. Underneath the bridge is space to park bicycles and an entrance to the internal building. The Hurricane building is designed for administration and other official purposes.
The main building that connects all the structures has been kept simple. This maintains the harmony and mellows the design complexities that other structures have. This makes it easier to accommodate classrooms for lectures and other activities. The library building holds space for books and reading tables. The upper part of this building works as a seminar room. Rest of the internal space between all the structures has been kept open. One can meet others, relax or spend some time with others.

Exhibition

The model was exhibited at the Fab Lab - Bremen in 2022. Some of the visitors were Robert Bücking ("bau- und stadtentwicklungspolitischer Sprecher") and Dr. Emanuel Herold ("Parlamentarischer Referent für Europa, Wirtschaft und Häfen ").

More

]]> 348 0 0 0 <![CDATA[City Campus Exhibition - 2022]]> https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/city-campus-exhibition-2022/ Tue, 29 Mar 2022 17:37:55 +0000 https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/?page_id=362

To showcase all the models of the exhibition, a video was created. For the creation of the video, a 3D model of the existing Am Brill space was extracted with photogrammetry. The model was then cleaned and provided to every team. Each team incorporated their own model in the provided 3D model of the Am Brill. These models where then compiled and programmed in Unity Game Engine. Unity Game Engine helped in fostering transition of between the models. The footage of the same was recorded. Later, all the footages was combined in DaVinci Resolve.

For the installation a Raspberry Pi board was made use of. The board was programmed in Python to run the video in loop with every boot up.

]]> 362 0 0 0 ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> ]]> <![CDATA[Entertainment Computing]]> https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/entertainment-computing/ Thu, 07 Apr 2022 10:14:01 +0000 https://kashishs1993.wordpress.com/?page_id=383

The following game was developed during the Summer Semester of 2020. The game was part of the course Entertainment Computing conducted by Prof. Dr. Rainer Malaka.

The game is built around the theme of "travelling," a concept provided by the professor during the course. Developed in one month by a team of three using Unity Engine, the game follows a school kid’s journey home after purchasing a game.

Along the way, the kid must overcome obstacles, collect coins, and protect the game while navigating the environment. The player can jump, walk, punch, and interact with NPCs, with the gameplay presented through an isometric camera perspective.

For my Master's thesis, I collaborated with the DLR in Bremerhaven. This project was presented and published at the MARESEC workshop in Bremerhaven.

Overview

Maritime computer vision is essential for applications such as autonomous navigation, infrastructure protection, and situational awareness. However, acquiring high-quality, diverse, and annotated real-world maritime datasets is challenging due to accessibility, cost, and environmental constraints. This project explores the potential of synthetic data generation using game engines to address these limitations.

By comparing Unity and Unreal Engine, this study examines their ability to create photorealistic maritime environments for training deep learning models in ship recognition. It also evaluates the impact of photorealistic effects, such as lighting conditions, water rendering, and lens distortions, on model performance.

Key Objectives

  • Evaluate Game Engines for Synthetic Data Generation: Comparing Unity Engine (HDRP) and Unreal Engine 5.3 to determine which produces more realistic maritime images.
  • Assess the Role of Photorealism in Computer Vision: Analysing how individual visual effects contribute to synthetic dataset quality and model accuracy.
  • Enhance Maritime Ship Detection Using YOLOv8: Testing whether integrating synthetic images with real-world datasets improves ship segmentation performance.

Methodology

  1. Recreating Real Maritime Scenes
    • A true-to-scale 3D model of the Doppelschleuse port in Bremerhaven, Germany, was developed using Blender and imported into both game engines.
    • The ShipSG dataset, containing 3,505 real maritime images, was used as a benchmark for comparison.
    • 3D models of ships were sourced and accurately scaled to match real-world vessels.
  2. Generating Synthetic Data
    • 52 real-world images were selected and replicated in Unity and Unreal, simulating different weather conditions, lighting, and water interactions.
    • Six photorealistic variations were tested, altering factors such as sunlight, lens distortion, water properties, and colour.
    • Unity’s Perception Package was used for auto-annotations, while Unreal Engine required manual annotation.
  3. Benchmarking Performance with YOLOv8
    • The mean Average Precision (mAP) of YOLOv8 was used to evaluate how well synthetic datasets performed compared to real images.
    • The highest-performing synthetic datasets were used to augment the real ShipSG dataset and retrain the YOLOv8 model.

Key Findings & Results

  • Best Performing Dataset: Synthetic images from Unity with manual annotations and full photorealistic effectsachieved the highest accuracy (mAP 72.3%).
  • Effect of Photorealism: Removing water realism or sunlight significantly reduced accuracy, demonstrating that high-fidelity effects are essential.
  • Impact of Data Augmentation: Adding the best synthetic dataset to the training process improved model accuracy by 0.4%, highlighting the value of synthetic data in maritime computer vision.
  • Challenges with Auto-Annotation: Unity’s automatic annotation tool included submerged ship hulls, leading to mismatches with real-world labelling, emphasising the need for better annotation strategies.

Significance & Future Directions

This research highlights the growing potential of synthetic data in maritime AI applications, paving the way for:

  • Improved training datasets without costly real-world data collection.
  • Game engines as powerful tools for scalable dataset generation.
  • Future advancements in maritime computer vision, including complex weather simulations and refined water physics.

This study provides a valuable reference for researchers, developers, and maritime AI practitioners looking to leverage synthetic data for enhanced situational awareness and ship recognition.

Summary

Tiltification is a multi-modal spirit level app designed to make sonification—a method of conveying information through sound—more accessible and widely recognised. Developed as part of the "Sonification Apps" project at the University of Bremen, the app utilises psychoacoustic sonification to provide real-time auditory feedback on a device’s tilt angles, enabling users to level surfaces or capture perfectly horizontal photos.

Unlike conventional spirit level tools, Tiltification enhances usability through detailed auditory feedback, making it particularly beneficial for individuals with visual impairments or reading disabilities. The app is available on iOS and Android, ensuring widespread accessibility.

Key Features

  • Auditory and Visual Feedback: Provides real-time sonification for precise levelling.
  • Enhanced Accessibility: Designed with features to assist visually impaired users.
  • Cross-Platform Availability: Available on Apple and Google app stores.
  • Educational Impact: Aims to familiarise users with sonification beyond scientific contexts.

Tiltification serves as a step towards integrating sonification into mainstream applications, demonstrating its potential as a practical and intuitive interface for real-world tasks.
